{"id":"0909.1861","submitter":"Fotini Markopoulou Kalamara","authors":"Fotini Markopoulou","title":"Space does not exist, so time can","comments":"Third prize of the FQXi 'The Nature of Time' Essay Contest","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is often said that in general relativity time does not exist. This is\nbecause the Einstein equations generate motion in time that is a symmetry of\nthe theory, not true time evolution. In quantum gravity, the timelessness of\ngeneral relativity clashes with time in quantum theory and leads to the\n``problem of time'' which, in its various forms, is the main obstacle to a\nsuccessful quantum theory of gravity. I argue that the problem of time is a\nparadox, stemming from an unstated faulty premise. Our faulty assumption is\nthat space is real. I propose that what does not fundamentally exist is not\ntime but space, geometry and gravity. The quantum theory of gravity will be\nspaceless, not timeless. If we are willing to throw out space, we can keep time\nand the trade is worth it.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 Sep 2009 02:32:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-09-11"}
